The key insight is that elements in the center of `A ⊗[k] B` that come from `A` (via the canonical embedding) must commute with all elements. Since `A` is commutative and `B` is central over `k`, the center of `A ⊗[k] B` over `A` should be exactly `A ⊗[k] (center of B over k) = A ⊗[k] k ≅ A`.

